doc.ContractDescription: IGF::OT::IGF VISN 4 TRASH REMOVAL SERVICES ADDITIONAL QUANTITIES ORDER/CORRECTING ORIGINAL ORDER.

GOALS AND OBJECTIVES VENUS TODAY HAS LESS THAN 30 PPMV OF WATER VAPOR IN ITS ATMOSPHERE, OR APPROXIMATELY 105 TIMES LESS WATER THAN EARTH HAS IN ITS OCEANS. BUT VENUS IS WIDELY BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN INITIALLY ENDOWED WITH LARGE QUANTITIES OF WATER AS A CONSEQUENCE OF ACCRETION OF WATER-RICH PLANETESIMALS FROM THE ASTEROID BELT OR BEYOND. THIS HYPOTHESIS IS SUPPORTED BY A MEASURED D/H RATIO ON VENUS THAT IS 150 TIMES HIGHER THAN THAT IN EARTH'S OCEANS. HOW VENUS LOST ITS WATER HAS BEEN THE TOPIC OF SEVERAL PREVIOUS STUDIES. IT COULD HAVE EXPERIENCED EITHER A 'RUNAWAY GREENHOUSE' IN WHICH THE OCEANS EVAPORATED ENTIRELY OR A 'MOIST GREENHOUSE' IN WHICH THE STRATOSPHERE BECAME WET AND WATER VAPOR WAS PHOTODISSOCIATED, AFTER WHICH HYDROGEN ESCAPED TO SPACE IN A HYDRODYNAMIC OUTFLOW. RECENTLY, HAMANO ET AL. (NATURE, 2013) HAVE ARGUED THAT WATER LOSS FROM VENUS OCCURRED DURING AND IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING ACCRETION, MAKING THIS PHENOMENON PART OF THE PLANETARY FORMATION PROCESS, AND THEREBY MAKING THIS PROBLEM RELEVANT TO NASA'S EMERGING WORLDS RESEARCH PROGRAM. SINCE THESE EARLY STUDIES, SEVERAL THINGS HAVE CHANGED. LECONTE ET AL. (NATURE, 2013) HAVE USED A 3-D CLIMATE MODEL TO ARGUE THAT THE 'MOIST GREENHOUSE' COULD NOT HAVE OCCURRED ON VENUS BECAUSE THE TROPOPAUSE WAS MUCH COLDER THAN SUGGESTED BY EARLIER STUDIES. OTHERS (E.G., TIAN ET AL., SCIENCE, 2005) HAVE ARGUED THAT HYDRODYNAMIC ESCAPE OF HYDROGEN WAS SLOWER THAN PREVIOUSLY CALCULATED. RECENT CALCULATIONS USING MORE SOPHISTICATED 1-D HYDRODYNAMIC MODELS (KURAMOTO ET AL., EPSL, 2013; ERKAEV ET AL., ASTROBIOL., 2013) HAVE PRODUCED CONFLICTING RESULTS CONCERNING HYDROGEN ESCAPE RATES. OTHER CALCULATIONS USING 2- AND 3-D HYDRODYNAMIC MODELS TO EXAMINE ESCAPE OF HYDROGEN FROM HOT JUPITERS HAVE DEMONSTRATED THAT GEOMETRY ALSO PLAYS A MAJOR ROLE IN DETERMINING ESCAPE RATES. WE PROPOSE TO REVISIT THE QUESTION OF WATER LOSS FROM VENUS WITH UPDATED MODELS FOR BOTH THE UPPER AND LOWER VENUS ATMOSPHERE. FOR THE LOWER ATMOSPHERE, WE WILL UPDATE OUR EXISTING 1-D CLIMATE MODEL TO INCLUDE ABSORPTION COEFFICIENTS THAT ARE VALID DOWN TO PRESSURES OF 10-6 BAR AND TEMPERATURES OF 100 K. WE WILL USE THIS MODEL TO ACCURATELY CALCULATE TEMPERATURES AT HIGH ALTITUDES IN WATER-RICH ATMOSPHERES. IF NECESSARY, WE WILL MODIFY THIS MODEL TO USE A RADIATIVE TRANSFER METHOD FROM THE STELLAR PHYSICS LITERATURE, FEAUTRIER S METHOD, AND USE IT TO LOOK AT NON-LTE EFFECTS. IN THE UPPER ATMOSPHERE, WE WILL MODIFY OUR EXISTING, SUBSONIC HYDRODYNAMIC ESCAPE CODE (TIAN ET AL., JGR., 2008) BY INCLUDING A SECOND FLUID, THEREBY REGAINING THE CAPABILITY OF CALCULATING A DIFFUSION LIMIT. IN COLLABORATION WITH COLLEAGUES AT THE UNIVERSITY OF ROCHESTER, WE WILL ALSO EMPLOY AN ADAPTIVE MESH REFINEMENT MULTI-PHYSICS GODUNOV-TYPE CODE ASTROBEAR (CUNNINGHAM ET AL., APJS, 2009, CARROLL-NELLENBACH ET AL., J. COMP. PHYS., 2013) TO EXAMINE THE ESCAPE OF HYDROGEN AT HIGH LEVELS OF SOLAR EUV HEATING. ASTROBEAR WAS DEVELOPED TO SIMULATE STRONGLY SHOCKED MULTICOMPONENT ASTROPHYSICAL FLUIDS AND IS WELL SUITED FOR SIMULATING TRANSONIC ESCAPING FLOWS. IT CAN BE RUN IN 1-, 2-, OR 3-DIMENSIONS TO EXAMINE GEOMETRICAL INFLUENCES ON THE ESCAPE RATE. WE WILL USE THESE MODELS TO SHED NEW LIGHT ON HOW VENUS EVOLVED TO ITS PRESENT, BONE-DRY STATE AND TO DETERMINE WHETHER AN EXOPLANET AT A PARTICULAR DISTANCE FROM ITS HOST STAR WILL EVOLVE INTO AN EXO-EARTH OR AN EXO-VENUS.
